[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(17) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "As for us . . .",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—Better, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Still do our eyes waste away, looking for our vain help.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "In our watching.—Better, upon our watch-tower. (Comp. Habakkuk 2:1.) The people of Judah are represented as looking out for the approach of an ally, probably Egypt (Jeremiah 37:7), and looking in vain.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "In our watching.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Better, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "upon our watch-tower. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "(Comp. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Habakkuk 2:1",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".) The people of Judah are represented as looking out for the approach of an ally, probably Egypt (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Jeremiah 37:7",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "), and looking in vain.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Lamentations 4:17",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Lamentations 4:17",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "As for us, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "&c. — The prophet, after having digressed in the last five verses to make observation on the wickedness of those who had been the principal cause of the national ruin, here returns again to the lamentable description of the particulars. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Our eyes as yet failed for our vain help — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The help of the Egyptians, which they had expected in vain. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "In our watching we have watched — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "We have long waited with eager desire and expectation; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "for a nation that could not save us — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "For succours from a people who at last have wofully disappointed us.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "4:13-20 Nothing ripens a people more for ruin, nor fills the measure faster, than the sins of priests and prophets. The king himself cannot escape, for Divine vengeance pursues him. Our anointed King alone is the life of our souls; we may safely live under his shadow, and rejoice in Him in the midst of our enemies, for He is the true God and eternal life.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
